'''Virgínia de Bivar Robertes Rau''' (December 4/9, 1907 – November 2, 1973) was a Portuguese archaeologist and historian. She was an expert on Portuguese and Portuguese colonial history and author of many history books.
She was the daughter of Luís Rau, Jr. (1865–1943) of German descent, and his wife Matilde de Bivar de Paula Robertes (1879–1961) of Spanish descent, who married in Lisbon in 1902. She enrolled in the Faculty of Letters of the [[University of Lisbon]] in 1927, but the following year went aboard, where she attended several courses including at the [[University of Toulouse]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Grande enciclopédia portuguesa e brasileira: actualização|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wkIZAQAAIAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Editorial Enciclopédia|language=Portuguese}}</ref> In 1939, due to the beginning of the Second World War, she returned to Lisbon, where she joined the Historical and Philosophical Sciences of the Faculty of Arts. A member of the [[Academia Portuguesa da História]], Rau published a vast collection of works on Portuguese and colonial medieval and modern history.<ref>GARCIA, José Manuel. RAU, Virgínia. ''Estudos Sobre a História do Sal Português'' (in Portuguese). Lisboa : Editorial Presença, 1984.</ref> On July 2, 1969, she was awarded the rank of Grand Officer of the [[Order of Public Instruction (Portugal)|Order of Public Instruction]]. ''Portuguese Studies Review'' cites her as a pioneer of the historiographical research of Timor governor {{ill|António Coelho Guerreiro|de}}, after a work she published in 1956.<ref name="Issue)2005">{{cite book|title=Portuguese Studies Review, Vol. 12, No. 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nuzVBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA38|date=22 February 2005|publisher=Baywolf Press|page=38|id=GGKEY:7BRBGWRYNQ1}}</ref> She has also commented on the economic history of Brazil and Angola.<ref name="RichardsonSilva2014">{{cite book|last1=Richardson|first1=David|last2=Silva|first2=Filipa Ribeiro da|title=Networks and Trans-Cultural Exchange: Slave Trading in the South Atlantic, 1590–1867|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yXSjBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA124|date=28 November 2014|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-28058-8|page=124}}</ref>
